e actions of the few and to reveal the legacy of violence that has been obscured by more valiant memories in the public sphere. In exploring the ways that spatial and literary texts replace lynching with proclamations of innocence and regret, Lightweis-Goff argues that racial violence is an incompletely erupted trauma of American life whose very hiddenness links the past to still-present practices of segregation and exclusion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aLynching -- United States -- History. 0aLynchingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRace relations in literature. 0aUnited States -- Race relations. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438436302423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438436302/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles